<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Drum drive diagnostic</p>
    <h2>The motor runs, the drum won't turn. Five components are doing the work.</h2>

    <p>A dryer that hums or runs but won't tumble is the second most common dryer service call we make. The control board is fine, the door switch is closed, the motor is energized. But the drum sits still or thumps and barely rotates. Five components share responsibility for spinning the drum: drive belt, idler pulley, drive pulley, drum rollers, and drive motor. The diagnostic order matters because the cheapest parts (belt, idler) fail first and the expensive parts (motor, bearing) fail last.</p>

    <p>Our techs service no-tumble dryers across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside. Both gas and electric (the drum drive system is identical on gas and electric models, only the heating system differs). All major brands: Whirlpool, GE, Samsung, LG, Maytag, Electrolux, Bosch, Frigidaire, KitchenAid, Miele, Thermador, Speed Queen, and others.</p>

    <p>$89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair. BHGS #A49573. EPA 608 Universal #1346255700410. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 FAILURE TREE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Failure tree</p>
    <h2>Five components, ranked by failure frequency.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Listen first. The sound the dryer makes when you press start tells us which component to test first.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Quiet hum, drum spins freely by hand: drive belt</h3>
    <p>Most common no-tumble cause across all brands. The belt is a thin rubber loop that wraps around the drum, the idler pulley, and the drive pulley on the motor shaft. Year 5 to 10 typical lifespan. When it breaks, the motor runs (you hear the hum) but nothing connects the motor torque to the drum. Replacement runs $185 to $325 including idler pulley inspection. We replace belt plus idler together as a standard procedure because the idler pulley wear is what kills belts early.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Loud thumping or grinding, drum partially turns: drum rollers</h3>
    <p>Year 7 to 12 typical. Most dryers have two rear drum rollers; some have four (rear plus front). The rollers are small wheels with internal bearings that support the drum. When the bearings wear, the rollers either seize (loud grinding) or develop flat spots (loud thumping). We replace all rollers as a set ($145 to $245 installed) because partial replacement gets you a callback within months.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Squealing or grinding from idler area: idler pulley</h3>
    <p>Year 5 to 8 typical. The idler pulley keeps tension on the belt. When its internal bearing wears, it squeals during operation, then eventually seizes. A seized idler stresses the belt until it snaps. We replace idler plus belt together ($185 to $285) because doing one without the other is poor economics on a year 8+ dryer.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Silent or single click, drum doesn't move at all: drive motor</h3>
    <p>Year 12+ typical. Drive motor failures are much rarer than belt or roller failures. Symptom: complete silence when you press start, or a single click followed by silence. The motor windings have failed open. We confirm with a multimeter resistance test before quoting. Motor replacement runs $345 to $525 depending on brand.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Loud rumble that gets worse over weeks: drum bearing or rear seal</h3>
    <p>Year 10+ typical. The drum spins on a rear bearing or felt seal. When that wears, the drum scrapes the cabinet at the rear, producing a deep rumbling sound. This is the most labor-intensive dryer repair. Cost runs $245 to $385.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 DIAGNOSTIC -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Diagnostic order</p>
    <h2>How we diagnose no-tumble in 15 to 25 minutes.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Listen test.</strong> Press start. Quiet hum points to belt or motor. Loud thumping points to rollers. Squealing points to idler. Silence points to motor or door switch.</li>
      <li><strong>Manual drum rotation test.</strong> With power off, rotate the drum by hand. Free spin points to belt failure. Heavy resistance points to roller seizure. Severe scraping points to drum bearing.</li>
      <li><strong>Belt visual inspection.</strong> Pull off the rear or top access panel and look at the belt. Broken belt is obvious. Stretched but intact belt typically pairs with worn idler pulley.</li>
      <li><strong>Idler pulley spin test.</strong> With belt off, spin the idler pulley by hand. Smooth rotation: idler okay. Grinding or wobbling: replace.</li>
      <li><strong>Roller spin test.</strong> Manually rotate each drum roller. Smooth rotation: okay. Grinding, wobbling, or seized: replace as a set.</li>
      <li><strong>Motor winding test.</strong> If listen test pointed to motor, multimeter ohm test on the motor windings. Open circuit: motor failed.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Once the failed component is identified, we replace it and run a no-load tumble test for 5 minutes to confirm smooth operation. The whole repair typically runs 60 to 120 minutes depending on which component failed.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 PRICING -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
