  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 BRANDS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Brand notes</p>
    <h2>No-tumble patterns by brand.</h2>

    <ul class="reasons-list">
      <li><strong>Whirlpool, Maytag, KitchenAid (Whirlpool family).</strong> 29-inch belt is the standard wear part. Drum rollers at year 8 to 10 typical. Cabrio and Duet families share the same drum drive parts platform.</li>
      <li><strong>GE.</strong> 27-inch belt standard. Idler pulley wear pattern at year 6 to 8 is the dominant cause of belt breakage on GE units.</li>
      <li><strong>Samsung.</strong> DV series uses a unique tensioner design. Belt failures often come from tensioner spring fatigue. We replace spring and belt together on year 8+ Samsung dryers.</li>
      <li><strong>LG.</strong> DLE and DLG models share parts. Drum bearing pattern at year 10 to 12 is more visible on LG than other brands because the bearing design has less margin.</li>
      <li><strong>Electrolux, Frigidaire (Electrolux family).</strong> Drum roller failures dominate. The roller bearings on this platform have a year 7 to 9 wear pattern that's tighter than other brands.</li>
      <li><strong>Bosch.</strong> European-architecture dryers have a different drum drive layout. Belt and roller diagnostic principles still apply, but parts platforms differ from US-market brands.</li>
      <li><strong>Miele, Thermador.</strong> Premium tier. Drum drive components last year 12 to 15 typical. Parts cost more but availability through SoCal distribution is solid.</li>
      <li><strong>Speed Queen.</strong> Built tougher. Belt and roller pattern often year 12+. When they do fail, parts are easy to source and labor is straightforward.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 FAQ -->
